        {
          "@type": "FAQPage",
          "mainEntity": [
            {
              "@type": "Question",
              "acceptedAnswer": {
                "@type": "Answer",
                "text": "Yes. Many women with endometriosis conceive — naturally in milder cases, and with IVF, which is often the most effective treatment, in more significant disease."
              },
              "name": "Can I get pregnant with endometriosis?"
            },
            {
              "@type": "Question",
              "acceptedAnswer": {
                "@type": "Answer",
                "text": "It depends on the stage, your ovarian reserve, pain and age. Sometimes surgery helps; often, especially with reduced reserve, going directly to IVF is better. We advise individually."
              },
              "name": "Should I have surgery or go straight to IVF?"
            },
            {
              "@type": "Question",
              "acceptedAnswer": {
                "@type": "Answer",
                "text": "It can, and ovarian endometriomas and surgery can reduce egg reserve, which is why we protect the ovaries and sometimes recommend egg freezing."
              },
              "name": "Does endometriosis affect egg quality?"
            },
            {
              "@type": "Question",
              "acceptedAnswer": {
                "@type": "Answer",
                "text": "Yes. IVF bypasses several ways endometriosis affects fertility and is frequently the most successful route to pregnancy."
              },
              "name": "Is IVF effective for endometriosis?"
            },
            {
              "@type": "Question",
              "acceptedAnswer": {
                "@type": "Answer",
                "text": "Treatment often improves pain, though endometriosis can recur. Pain control and fertility are planned together according to your priorities."
              },
              "name": "Will treating endometriosis cure my pain?"
            }
          ]
        },
